Under normoxic conditions, HIFalpha is ubiquinated by the Von Hippel-Lindau (VHL) tumor suppressor gene product and then targeted for proteasomal degradation, but under hypoxia the interaction between HIFalpha and VHL is abrogated.

The interaction between pVHL and HIFalpha requires the hydroxylation on either of two prolyl residues by members of the egl nine homolog (EglN) family (also called prolyl hydoxylase domain containing (PHDs) or HIF prolyl hydroxylases (HPHs)).

In the presence of oxygen, HIFalpha is hydroxylated by prolyl hydroxylase (PHD) and then binds to VHL for proteasome mediated degradation through the formation of EC 2 V (Elongin BC-Cul2-VHL) E3 ubiquitin ligase complex XREF_BIBR - XREF_BIBR.

The interaction between pVHL and HIFalpha requires that HIFalpha be hydroxylated on either of two prolyl residues by members of the EglN family (also called PHDs or HPHs), which areoxygen dependent enzymes that have evolved to respond to changes in oxygen over a physiologically relevant range in an intracellular milieu ().
Thus, under normoxic conditions, HIFalpha is bound by the VHL protein, resulting in ubiquitination and proteasomal degradation of HIFalpha.

In normoxia, HIFalpha undergoes prolyl hydroxylation and binds to an ubiquitin E3-ligase, the von Hippel-Lindau (VHL) protein, which leads to polyubiquitination and rapid proteosomal degradation of HIFalpha XREF_BIBR, XREF_BIBR.

Within the complex, PHD2 exhibits increased hydroxylase activity towards HIFalpha, resulting in enhanced interaction between HIFalpha and VHL, owing to the higher affinity of VHL for hydroxylated HIFalpha.
pVHL only binds to HIFalpha if one of two prolyl residues is hydroxylated by members of the EglN family (also called PHDs or HPHs) XREF_BIBR, XREF_BIBR, XREF_BIBR, XREF_BIBR.

The mechanism of cellular oxygen sensing is bound to this interaction, since the recognition and binding of pVHL to HIFalpha requires oxygen dependent hydroxylation of conserved proline residues on HIFalpha by HIF prolyl hydroxylases (PHD1-3) XREF_BIBR - XREF_BIBR.
Overexpression of PHF20 is proposed to drive constitutive NF-kappaB activation in some tumors ().
Herein, we describe a novel role of PHF20 in NF-kappaB signalling : PHF20 promotes NF-kappaB transcriptional activity by interacting with p65 in a methylation dependent manner.
Such observations thus indicate that PHF20 is able to upregulate NF-kappaB activation in a canonical pathway.
To gain further insight into the molecular mechanisms underlying PHF20 mediated NF-kappaB activation, we next examined the phosphorylation and degradation of IkappaBalpha.

These observations clearly suggest that in the nucleus the potency of PHF20 to interrupt the assembly of p65 with IkappaBalpha through enhanced p65 phosphorylation and subsequently its acetylation contributes to prolong NF-kappaB response.
Thus, we next attempted to investigate the role of p65 methylation in the PHF20 mediated NF-kappaB activation.
These results suggest that K221 methylation of p65, which is required for its interaction with PHF20, has a critical role in PHF20 mediated NF-kappaB activation.

Such observations indicate that PHF20 functions through the recognition of K221 dimethylation of p65, thus revealing a previously unknown mechanism for p65 methylation mediated NF-kappaB hyperactivation in the nucleus.
Such observations thus reveal a novel mechanism through which PHF20 promotes NF-kappaB activation.
